# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: computational-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] In physics, different theories based on mathematical models provide very precise predictions on how systems behave.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] Unfortunately, it is often the case that solving the mathematical model for a particular system in order to produce a useful prediction is not feasible.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] This can occur, for instance, when the solution does not have a closed-form expression, or is too complicated.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] In such cases, numerical approximations are required.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] There is a debate about the status of computation within the scientific method.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] Sometimes it is regarded as more akin to theoretical physics; some others regard computer simulation as "computer experiments", yet still others consider it an intermediate or different branch between theoretical and experimental physics, a third way that supplements theory and experiment.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] While computers can be used in experiments for the measurement and recording (and storage) of data, this clearly does not constitute a computational approach.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] Computational physics problems are in general very difficult to solve exactly.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] This is due to several (mathematical) reasons: lack of algebraic and/or analytic solvability, complexity, and chaos.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] On the more advanced side, mathematical perturbation theory is also sometimes used (a working is shown for this particular example here).
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] In addition, the computational cost and computational complexity for many-body problems (and their classical counterparts) tend to grow quickly.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] A macroscopic system typically has a size of the order of $10^{23}$ constituent particles, so it is somewhat of a problem.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] Solving quantum mechanical problems is generally of exponential order in the size of the system and for classical N-body it is of order N-squared.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] Finally, many physical systems are inherently nonlinear at best, and at worst chaotic: this means it can be difficult to ensure any numerical errors do not grow to the point of rendering the 'solution' useless.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] Because computational physics uses a broad class of problems, it is generally divided amongst the different mathematical problems it numerically solves, or the methods it applies.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] All these methods (and several others) are used to calculate physical properties of the modeled systems.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] Computational physics also borrows a number of ideas from computational chemistry - for example, the density functional theory used by computational solid state physicists to calculate properties of solids is basically the same as that used by chemists to calculate the properties of molecules.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] Furthermore, computational physics encompasses the tuning of the software/hardware structure to solve the problems (as the problems usually can be very large, in processing power need or in memory requests).
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] Computational solid state physics, for example, uses density functional theory to calculate properties of solids, a method similar to that used by chemists to study molecules.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] Other quantities of interest in solid state physics, such as the electronic band structure, magnetic properties and charge densities can be calculated by this and several methods, including the Luttinger-Kohn/k.p method and ab-initio methods.
[src:computational-physics/computational-physics] On top of advanced physics software, there are also a myriad of tools of analytics available for beginning students of physics such as the PASCO Capstone software.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The **Ising model** (or **Lenz–Ising model**), named after the physicists Ernst Ising and Wilhelm Lenz, is a mathematical model of ferromagnetism in statistical mechanics.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The model consists of discrete variables that represent magnetic dipole moments of atomic "spins" that can be in one of two states (+1 or −1).
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The spins are arranged in a graph, usually a lattice (where the local structure repeats periodically in all directions), allowing each spin to interact with its neighbors.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Neighboring spins that agree have a lower energy than those that disagree; the system tends to the lowest energy but heat disturbs this tendency, thus creating the possibility of different structural phases.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The two-dimensional square-lattice Ising model is one of the simplest statistical models to show a phase transition.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Though it is a highly simplified model of a magnetic material, the Ising model can still provide qualitative and sometimes quantitative results applicable to real physical systems, and in general, it can be seen as a specialization of Stanley's *n*-vector model for *n* = 1.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The Ising model was invented by the physicist Wilhelm Lenz (1920), who gave it as a problem to his student Ernst Ising.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The one-dimensional Ising model was solved by Ising (1925) alone in his 1924 thesis; it has no phase transition.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The two-dimensional square-lattice Ising model is much harder and was only given an analytic description much later, by Lars Onsager (1944).
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] It is usually solved by a transfer-matrix method, although there exists a very simple approach relating the model to a non-interacting fermionic quantum field theory.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] In dimensions greater than four, the phase transition of the Ising model is described by mean-field theory.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The solution to this model exhibited a new, unusual phase transition behavior, along with non-vanishing long-range and nearest-neighbor spin-spin correlations, deemed relevant to large neural networks as one of its possible applications.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The Ising problem without an external field can be equivalently formulated as a graph maximum cut (Max-Cut) problem that can be solved via combinatorial optimization.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Consider a set $\Lambda$ of lattice sites, each with a set of adjacent sites (e.g. a graph) forming a d -dimensional lattice.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] For each lattice site $k\in \Lambda$ there is a discrete variable $\sigma _{k}$ such that $\sigma _{k}\in \{-1,+1\}$ , representing the site's spin.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] A *spin configuration*, ${\sigma }=\{\sigma _{k}\}_{k\in \Lambda }$ is an assignment of spin value to each lattice site.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] For any two adjacent sites $i,j\in \Lambda$ there is an *interaction* $J_{ij}$ .
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Also a site $j\in \Lambda$ has an *external magnetic field* $h_{j}$ interacting with it.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] where the first sum is over pairs of adjacent spins (every pair is counted once).
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The notation $\langle ij\rangle$ indicates that sites i and j are nearest neighbors.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Note that the sign in the second term of the Hamiltonian above should actually be positive because the electron's magnetic moment is antiparallel to its spin, but the negative term is used conventionally.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The Ising Hamiltonian is an example of a pseudo-Boolean function; tools from the analysis of Boolean functions can be applied to describe and study it.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The configuration probabilities $P_{\beta }(\sigma )$ represent the probability that (in equilibrium) the system is in a state with configuration $\sigma$ .
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The minus sign on each term of the Hamiltonian function $H(\sigma )$ is conventional.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The system is called ferromagnetic or antiferromagnetic if all interactions are ferromagnetic or all are antiferromagnetic.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The original Ising models were ferromagnetic, and it is still often assumed that "Ising model" means a ferromagnetic Ising model.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] In a ferromagnetic Ising model, spins desire to be aligned: the configurations in which adjacent spins are of the same sign have higher probability.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] In an antiferromagnetic model, adjacent spins tend to have opposite signs.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The sign convention of *H*(σ) also explains how a spin site *j* interacts with the external field.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Namely, the spin site wants to line up with the external field.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Ising models are often examined without an external field interacting with the lattice, that is, *h* = 0 for all *j* in the lattice Λ.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] When the external field is zero everywhere, *h* = 0, the Ising model is symmetric under switching the value of the spin in all the lattice sites; a nonzero field breaks this symmetry.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Another common simplification is to assume that all of the nearest neighbors ⟨*ij*⟩ have the same interaction strength.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Then we can set *Jij* = *J* for all pairs *i*, *j* in Λ.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] A subset S of the vertex set V(G) of a weighted undirected graph G determines a cut of the graph G into S and its complementary subset G\S.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The size of the cut is the sum of the weights of the edges between S and G\S.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] A maximum cut size is at least the size of any other cut, varying S.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Here each vertex i of the graph is a spin site that takes a spin value $\sigma _{i}=\pm 1$ .
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] A given spin configuration $\sigma$ partitions the set of vertices $V(G)$ into two $\sigma$ -depended subsets, those with spin up $V^{+}$ and those with spin down $V^{-}$ .
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] We denote by $\delta (V^{+})$ the $\sigma$ -depended set of edges that connects the two complementary vertex subsets $V^{+}$ and $V^{-}$ .
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] where $W_{ij}$ denotes a weight of the edge $ij$ and the scaling 1/2 is introduced to compensate for double counting the same weights $W_{ij}=W_{ji}$ .
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] where the total sum in the first term does not depend on $\sigma$ , imply that minimizing $H(\sigma )$ in $\sigma$ is equivalent to minimizing $\sum _{ij\in \delta (V^{+})}J_{ij}$ .
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The most studied case of the Ising model is the translation-invariant ferromagnetic zero-field model on a *d*-dimensional lattice, namely, Λ = **Z***d*, *J**ij* = 1, *h* = 0.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] In his 1924 PhD thesis, Ising solved the model for the *d* = 1 case, which can be thought of as a linear horizontal lattice where each site only interacts with its left and right neighbor.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] In one dimension, the solution admits no phase transition.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] On the basis of this result, he incorrectly concluded that this model does not exhibit phase behaviour in any dimension.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The Ising model undergoes a phase transition between an ordered and a disordered phase in 2 dimensions or more.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This was first proven by Rudolf Peierls in 1936, using what is now called a **Peierls argument**.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The Ising model on a two-dimensional square lattice with no magnetic field was analytically solved by Lars Onsager (1944).
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Onsager obtained the correlation functions and free energy of the Ising model and announced the formula for the spontaneous magnetization for the 2-dimensional model in 1949 but did not give a derivation.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Yang (1952) gave the first published proof of this formula, using a limit formula for Fredholm determinants, proved in 1951 by Szegő in direct response to Onsager's work.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] A number of correlation inequalities have been derived rigorously for the Ising spin correlations (for general lattice structures), which have enabled mathematicians to study the Ising model both on and off criticality.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] where $\langle \sigma _{A}\rangle =\langle \prod _{j\in A}\sigma _{j}\rangle$ .
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] With $B=\emptyset$ , the special case $\langle \sigma _{A}\rangle \geq 0$ results.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This means that spins are positively correlated on the Ising ferromagnet.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] An immediate application of this is that the magnetization of any set of spins $\langle \sigma _{A}\rangle$ is increasing with respect to any set of coupling constants $J_{B}$ .
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This inequality can be used to establish the sharpness of phase transition for the Ising model.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This inequality is proven first for a type of positively-correlated percolation model, of which includes a representation of the Ising model.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] It is used to determine the critical temperatures of planar Potts model using percolation arguments (which includes the Ising model as a special case).
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] While the laws of chemical bonding made it clear to nineteenth century chemists that atoms were real, among physicists the debate continued well into the early twentieth century.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Atomists, notably James Clerk Maxwell and Ludwig Boltzmann, applied Hamilton's formulation of Newton's laws to large systems, and found that the statistical behavior of the atoms correctly describes room temperature gases.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] But classical statistical mechanics did not account for all of the properties of liquids and solids, nor of gases at low temperature.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Once modern quantum mechanics was formulated, atomism was no longer in conflict with experiment, but this did not lead to a universal acceptance of statistical mechanics, which went beyond atomism.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Josiah Willard Gibbs had given a complete formalism to reproduce the laws of thermodynamics from the laws of mechanics.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] But many faulty arguments survived from the 19th century, when statistical mechanics was considered dubious.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The lapses in intuition mostly stemmed from the fact that the limit of an infinite statistical system has many zero-one laws which are absent in finite systems: an infinitesimal change in a parameter can lead to big differences in the overall, aggregate behavior.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The exponential function is everywhere analytic as a function of β.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The sum of analytic functions is an analytic function.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This argument works for a finite sum of exponentials, and correctly establishes that there are no singularities in the free energy of a system of a finite size.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] For systems which are in the thermodynamic limit (that is, for infinite systems) the infinite sum can lead to singularities.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The convergence to the thermodynamic limit is fast, so that the phase behavior is apparent already on a relatively small lattice, even though the singularities are smoothed out by the system's finite size.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This was first established by Rudolf Peierls in the Ising model.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Shortly after Lenz and Ising constructed the Ising model, Peierls was able to explicitly show that a phase transition occurs in two dimensions.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] To do this, he compared the high-temperature and low-temperature limits.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] At infinite temperature (β = 0) all configurations have equal probability.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Each spin is completely independent of any other, and if typical configurations at infinite temperature are plotted so that plus/minus are represented by black and white, they look like television snow.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] For high, but not infinite temperature, there are small correlations between neighboring positions, the snow tends to clump a little bit, but the screen stays randomly looking, and there is no net excess of black or white.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] A bogus argument analogous to the argument in the last section now establishes that the *average* magnetization in the Ising model is always zero.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] So for every configuration with magnetization *M* there is a configuration with magnetization −*M* with equal probability.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The system should therefore spend equal amounts of time in the configuration with magnetization *M* as with magnetization −*M*.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] So the average magnetization (over all time) is zero.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] As before, this only proves that the average magnetization is zero at any finite volume.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] For an infinite system, fluctuations might not be able to push the system from a mostly plus state to a mostly minus with a nonzero probability.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] For very high temperatures, the magnetization is zero, as it is at infinite temperature.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] To see this, note that if spin A has only a small correlation ε with spin B, and B is only weakly correlated with C, but C is otherwise independent of A, the amount of correlation of A and C goes like ε2.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] For two spins separated by distance *L*, the amount of correlation goes as ε*L*, but if there is more than one path by which the correlations can travel, this amount is enhanced by the number of paths.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The number of paths of length *L* on a square lattice in *d* dimensions is $N(L)=(2d)^{L},$ since there are 2*d* choices for where to go at each step.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] A bound on the total correlation is given by the contribution to the correlation by summing over all paths linking two points, which is bounded above by the sum over all paths of length *L* divided by $\sum _{L}(2d)^{L}\varepsilon ^{L},$ which goes to zero when ε is small.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] At low temperatures (β ≫ 1) the configurations are near the lowest-energy configuration, the one where all the spins are plus or all the spins are minus.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Peierls asked whether it is statistically possible at low temperature, starting with all the spins minus, to fluctuate to a state where most of the spins are plus.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] For this to happen, droplets of plus spin must be able to congeal to make the plus state.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The energy of a droplet of plus spins in a minus background is proportional to the perimeter of the droplet L, where plus spins and minus spins neighbor each other.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] For a droplet with perimeter *L*, the area is somewhere between (*L* − 2)/2 (the straight line) and (*L*/4)2 (the square box).
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] For β sufficiently large, this exponentially suppresses long loops, so that they cannot occur, and the magnetization never fluctuates too far from −1.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] So Peierls established that the magnetization in the Ising model eventually defines superselection sectors, separated domains not linked by finite fluctuations.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Kramers and Wannier were able to show that the high-temperature expansion and the low-temperature expansion of the model are equal up to an overall rescaling of the free energy.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This allowed the phase-transition point in the two-dimensional model to be determined exactly (under the assumption that there is a unique critical point).
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] After Onsager's solution, Yang and Lee investigated the way in which the partition function becomes singular as the temperature approaches the critical temperature.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The original motivation for the model was the phenomenon of ferromagnetism.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Iron is magnetic; once it is magnetized it stays magnetized for a long time compared to any atomic time.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] In the 19th century, it was thought that magnetic fields are due to currents in matter, and Ampère postulated that permanent magnets are caused by permanent atomic currents.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The motion of classical charged particles could not explain permanent currents though, as shown by Larmor.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] In order to have ferromagnetism, the atoms must have permanent magnetic moments which are not due to the motion of classical charges.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Once the electron's spin was discovered, it was clear that the magnetism should be due to a large number of electron spins all oriented in the same direction.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] It was natural to ask how the electrons' spins all know which direction to point in, because the electrons on one side of a magnet don't directly interact with the electrons on the other side.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] They can only influence their neighbors.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The Ising model was designed to investigate whether a large fraction of the electron spins could be oriented in the same direction using only local forces.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The Ising model can be reinterpreted as a statistical model for the motion of atoms.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Since the kinetic energy depends only on momentum and not on position, while the statistics of the positions only depends on the potential energy, the thermodynamics of the gas only depends on the potential energy for each configuration of atoms.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] A coarse model is to make space-time a lattice and imagine that each position either contains an atom or it doesn't.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The space of configuration is that of independent bits *Bi*, where each bit is either 0 or 1 depending on whether the position is occupied or not.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] An attractive interaction reduces the energy of two nearby atoms.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] If the attraction is only between nearest neighbors, the energy is reduced by −4*JB**i**B**j* for each occupied neighboring pair.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The density of the atoms can be controlled by adding a chemical potential, which is a multiplicative probability cost for adding one more atom.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] A multiplicative factor in probability can be reinterpreted as an additive term in the logarithm – the energy.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The extra energy of a configuration with *N* atoms is changed by *μN*.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The probability cost of one more atom is a factor of exp(−*βμ*).
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] For lattices where every site has an equal number of neighbors, this is the Ising model with a magnetic field *h* = (*zJ* − *μ*)/2, where *z* is the number of neighbors.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] In biological systems, modified versions of the lattice gas model have been used to understand a range of binding behaviors.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] These include the binding of ligands to receptors in the cell surface, the binding of chemotaxis proteins to the flagellar motor, and the condensation of DNA.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The activity of neurons in the brain can be modelled statistically.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Each neuron at any time is either active + or inactive −.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The active neurons are those that send an action potential down the axon in any given time window, and the inactive ones are those that do not.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Following the general approach of Jaynes, a later interpretation of Schneidman, Berry, Segev and Bialek, is that the Ising model is useful for any model of neural function, because a statistical model for neural activity should be chosen using the principle of maximum entropy.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Given a collection of neurons, a statistical model which can reproduce the average firing rate for each neuron introduces a Lagrange multiplier for each neuron: $E=-\sum _{i}h_{i}S_{i}$ But the activity of each neuron in this model is statistically independent.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] To allow for pair correlations, when one neuron tends to fire (or not to fire) along with another, introduce pair-wise lagrange multipliers: $E=-{\tfrac {1}{2}}\sum _{ij}J_{ij}S_{i}S_{j}-\sum _{i}h_{i}S_{i}$ where $J_{ij}$ are not restricted to neighbors.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Note that this generalization of Ising model is sometimes called the quadratic exponential binary distribution in statistics.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This energy function only introduces probability biases for a spin having a value and for a pair of spins having the same value.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Higher order correlations are unconstrained by the multipliers.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] An activity pattern sampled from this distribution requires the largest number of bits to store in a computer, in the most efficient coding scheme imaginable, as compared with any other distribution with the same average activity and pairwise correlations.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This means that Ising models are relevant to any system which is described by bits which are as random as possible, with constraints on the pairwise correlations and the average number of 1s, which frequently occurs in both the physical and social sciences.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] With the Ising model the so-called spin glasses can also be described, by the usual Hamiltonian ${\textstyle H=-{\frac {1}{2}}\,\sum J_{i,k}\,S_{i}\,S_{k},}$ where the *S*-variables describe the Ising spins, while the *Ji,k* are taken from a random distribution.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] For spin glasses a typical distribution chooses antiferromagnetic bonds with probability *p* and ferromagnetic bonds with probability 1 − *p* (also known as the random-bond Ising model).
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] These bonds stay fixed or "quenched" even in the presence of thermal fluctuations.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] When *p* = 0 we have the original Ising model.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This system deserves interest in its own; particularly one has "non-ergodic" properties leading to strange relaxation behaviour.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Much attention has been also attracted by the related bond and site dilute Ising model, especially in two dimensions, leading to intriguing critical behavior.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The Ising model was instrumental in the development of the Hopfield network.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The original Ising model is a model for equilibrium.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Glauber in 1963 studied the Ising model evolving in time, as a process towards thermal equilibrium (Glauber dynamics), adding in the component of time.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] (Kaoru Nakano, 1971) and (Shun'ichi Amari, 1972), proposed to modify the weights of an Ising model by Hebbian learning rule as a model of associative memory.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The same idea was published by (William A.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Little, 1974), who was cited by Hopfield in his 1982 paper.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The Sherrington–Kirkpatrick model of spin glass, published in 1975, is the Hopfield network with random initialization.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Sherrington and Kirkpatrick found that it is highly likely for the energy function of the SK model to have many local minima.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] In the 1982 paper, Hopfield applied this recently developed theory to study the Hopfield network with binary activation functions.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] In a 1984 paper he extended this to continuous activation functions.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] It became a standard model for the study of neural networks through statistical mechanics.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The melt pond can be modelled by the Ising model; sea ice topography data bears rather heavily on the results.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The state variable is binary for a simple 2D approximation, being either water or ice.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The spin-spin correlation between sites (in general, m and n) on the tree was found to have a transition point when considered at the vertices (e.g.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] A and Ā, its reflection), their respective neighboring sites (such as B and its reflection), and between sites adjacent to the top and bottom extreme vertices of the two trees (e.g.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The model's behavior is also of relevance for any other divergent-convergent tree physical (or biological) system exhibiting a closed Cayley tree topology with an Ising-type of interaction.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This topology should not be ignored since its behavior for Ising models has been solved exactly, and presumably nature will have found a way of taking advantage of such simple symmetries at many levels of its designs.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] It was a natural and common belief among early neurophysicists (e.g.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The Ising model can often be difficult to evaluate numerically if there are many states in the system.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Since every spin site has ±1 spin, there are *2**L* different states that are possible.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This motivates the reason for the Ising model to be simulated using Monte Carlo methods.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Furthermore, the Hamiltonian is further simplified by assuming zero external field *h*, since many questions that are posed to be solved using the model can be answered in absence of an external field.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Given this Hamiltonian, quantities of interest such as the specific heat or the magnetization of the magnet at a given temperature can be calculated.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm is the most commonly used Monte Carlo algorithm to calculate Ising model estimations.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The algorithm first chooses *selection probabilities* *g*(μ, ν), which represent the probability that state ν is selected by the algorithm out of all states, given that one is in state μ.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] It then uses acceptance probabilities *A*(μ, ν) so that detailed balance is satisfied.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] If the new state ν is accepted, then we move to that state and repeat with selecting a new state and deciding to accept it.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This process is repeated until some stopping criterion is met, which for the Ising model is often when the lattice becomes ferromagnetic, meaning all of the sites point in the same direction.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] When implementing the algorithm, one must ensure that *g*(μ, ν) is selected such that ergodicity is met.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] In thermal equilibrium a system's energy only fluctuates within a small range.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This is the motivation behind the concept of **single-spin-flip dynamics**, which states that in each transition, we will only change one of the spin sites on the lattice.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Furthermore, by using single- spin-flip dynamics, one can get from any state to any other state by flipping each site that differs between the two states one at a time.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The maximum amount of change between the energy of the present state, *H*μ and any possible new state's energy *H*ν (using single-spin-flip dynamics) is 2*J* between the spin we choose to "flip" to move to the new state and that spin's neighbor.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Thus, in a 1D Ising model, where each site has two neighbors (left and right), the maximum difference in energy would be 4*J*.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Let *c* represent the *lattice coordination number*; the number of nearest neighbors that any lattice site has.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] We assume that all sites have the same number of neighbors due to periodic boundary conditions.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] It is important to note that the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm does not perform well around the critical point due to critical slowing down.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Other techniques such as multigrid methods, Niedermayer's algorithm, Swendsen–Wang algorithm, or the Wolff algorithm are required in order to resolve the model near the critical point; a requirement for determining the critical exponents of the system.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Specifically for the Ising model and using single-spin-flip dynamics, one can establish the following.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Since there are *L* total sites on the lattice, using single-spin-flip as the only way we transition to another state, we can see that there are a total of *L* new states ν from our present state μ.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The algorithm assumes that the selection probabilities are equal to the *L* states: *g*(μ, ν) = 1/*L*.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Metropolis sets the larger of *A*(μ, ν) or *A*(ν, μ) to be 1.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Flip the value of the spin and calculate the new contribution.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] If the new energy is less, keep the flipped value.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] The change in energy *H*ν − *H*μ only depends on the value of the spin and its nearest graph neighbors.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] So if the graph is not too connected, the algorithm is fast.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] This process will eventually produce a pick from the distribution.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] It is possible to view the Ising model as a Markov chain, as the immediate probability *P*β(ν) of transitioning to a future state ν only depends on the present state μ.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p01] Furthermore, since the energy equation *H*σ change only depends on the nearest-neighbor interaction strength *J*, the Ising model and its variants such the Sznajd model can be seen as a form of a voter model for opinion dynamics.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The thermodynamic limit exists as long as the interaction decay is $J_{ij}\sim |i-j|^{-\alpha }$ with α > 1.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] In the nearest neighbor case (with periodic or free boundary conditions) an exact solution is available.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] For *T* → 0, though, the inverse correlation length *c*(β) vanishes.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The proof of this result is a simple computation.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] hence it decays exponentially as soon as *T* ≠ 0; but for *T* = 0, i.e. in the limit β → ∞ there is no decay.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] If *h* ≠ 0 we need the transfer matrix method.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] For the periodic boundary conditions case is the following.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] This gives the formula of the free energy above.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] In the thermodynamics limit for the non-interaction case (J = 0), we got $Z_{N}\to (\lambda _{1})^{N}=(2\cosh \beta h)^{N},$ as the answer for the open-boundary Ising model.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The energy of the lowest state is −*JL*, when all the spins are the same.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] For any other configuration, the extra energy is equal to 2*J* times the number of sign changes that are encountered when scanning the configuration from left to right.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] If we designate the number of sign changes in a configuration as *k*, the difference in energy from the lowest energy state is 2*k*.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] Since the energy is additive in the number of flips, the probability *p* of having a spin-flip at each position is independent.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The problem is reduced to independent biased coin tosses.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] This essentially completes the mathematical description.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] From the description in terms of independent tosses, the statistics of the model for long lines can be understood.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] Each domain is of average length exp(2β).
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The length of a domain is distributed exponentially, since there is a constant probability at any step of encountering a flip.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The domains never become infinite, so a long system is never magnetized.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] Each step reduces the correlation between a spin and its neighbor by an amount proportional to *p*, so the correlations fall off exponentially.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The partition function is the volume of configurations, each configuration weighted by its Boltzmann weight.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] A sign of a phase transition is a non-analytic free energy, so the one-dimensional model does not have a phase transition.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] To express the Ising Hamiltonian using a quantum mechanical description of spins, we replace the spin variables with their respective Pauli matrices.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] However, depending on the direction of the magnetic field, we can create a transverse-field or longitudinal-field Hamiltonian.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The transverse-field model experiences a phase transition between an ordered and disordered regime at *J* ~ *h*.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] Since the roles of *h* and *J* are switched, the Hamiltonian undergoes a transition at *J* = *h*.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] When there is no external field, we can derive a functional equation that $f(\beta ,0)=f(\beta )$ satisfies using renormalization.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] Specifically, let $Z_{N}(\beta ,J)$ be the partition function with N sites.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] When $\beta$ is small, we have $f(\beta )\approx \ln 2$ , so we can numerically evaluate $f(\beta )$ by iterating the functional equation until K is small.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] In the ferromagnetic case there is a phase transition.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] At low temperature, the Peierls argument proves positive magnetization for the nearest neighbor case and then, by the Griffiths inequality, also when longer range interactions are added.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] Meanwhile, at high temperature, the cluster expansion gives analyticity of the thermodynamic functions.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] In the nearest-neighbor case, the free energy was exactly computed by Onsager.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The spin-spin correlation functions were computed by McCoy and Wu.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] From this expression for the free energy, all thermodynamic functions of the model can be calculated by using an appropriate derivative.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The 2D Ising model was the first model to exhibit a continuous phase transition at a positive temperature.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] When the interaction energies $J_{1}$ , $J_{2}$ are both negative, the Ising model becomes an antiferromagnet.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] Since the square lattice is bi-partite, it is invariant under this change when the magnetic field $h=0$ , so the free energy and critical temperature are the same for the antiferromagnetic case.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] For the triangular lattice, which is not bi-partite, the ferromagnetic and antiferromagnetic Ising model behave notably differently.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] Specifically, around a triangle, it is impossible to make all 3 spin-pairs antiparallel, so the antiferromagnetic Ising model cannot reach the minimal energy state.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] This is an example of geometric frustration.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] where $J_{1}$ and $J_{2}$ are horizontal and vertical interaction energies.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] A complete derivation was only given in 1951 by Yang (1952) using a limiting process of transfer matrix eigenvalues.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The proof was subsequently greatly simplified in 1963 by Montroll, Potts, and Ward using Szegő's limit formula for Toeplitz determinants by treating the magnetization as the limit of correlation functions.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] At the critical point, the two-dimensional Ising model is a two-dimensional conformal field theory.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The spin and energy correlation functions are described by a minimal model, which has been exactly solved.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] In three as in two dimensions, the most studied case of the Ising model is the translation-invariant model on a cubic lattice with nearest-neighbor coupling in the zero magnetic field.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] Many theoreticians searched for an analytical three-dimensional solution for many decades, which would be analogous to Onsager's solution in the two-dimensional case.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] Such a solution has not been found until now, although there is no proof that it may not exist.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] In three dimensions, the Ising model was shown to have a representation in terms of non-interacting fermionic strings by Alexander Polyakov and Vladimir Dotsenko.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] This construction has been carried on the lattice, and the continuum limit, conjecturally describing the critical point, is unknown.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] In three as in two dimensions, Peierls' argument shows that there is a phase transition.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] This phase transition is rigorously known to be continuous (in the sense that correlation length diverges and the magnetization goes to zero), and is called the critical point.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] It is believed that the critical point can be described by a renormalization group fixed point of the Wilson-Kadanoff renormalization group transformation.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] It is also believed that the phase transition can be described by a three-dimensional unitary conformal field theory, as evidenced by Monte Carlo simulations, exact diagonalization results in quantum models, and quantum field theoretical arguments.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] This conformal field theory describing the three-dimensional Ising critical point is under active investigation using the method of the conformal bootstrap.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] This method currently yields the most precise information about the structure of the critical theory (see Ising critical exponents).
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] In 2000, Sorin Istrail of Sandia National Laboratories proved that the spin glass Ising model on a nonplanar lattice is NP-complete.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] That is, assuming **P** ≠ **NP,** the general spin glass Ising model is exactly solvable only in planar cases, so solutions for dimensions higher than two are also intractable.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] Istrail's result only concerns the spin glass model with spatially varying couplings, and tells nothing about Ising's original ferromagnetic model with equal couplings.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] In any dimension, the Ising model can be productively described by a locally varying mean field.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The field is defined as the average spin value over a large region, but not so large so as to include the entire system.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The field still has slow variations from point to point, as the averaging volume moves.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] These fluctuations in the field are described by a continuum field theory in the infinite system limit.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] The accuracy of this approximation improves as the dimension becomes larger.
[src:computational-physics/ising-model-p02] A deeper understanding of how the Ising model behaves, going beyond mean-field approximations, can be achieved using renormalization group methods.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The **lattice Boltzmann methods (LBM)**, originated from the lattice gas automata (LGA) method (Hardy-Pomeau-Pazzis and Frisch-Hasslacher-Pomeau models), is a class of computational fluid dynamics (CFD) methods for fluid simulation.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Instead of solving the Navier–Stokes equations directly, a fluid density on a lattice is simulated with streaming and collision (relaxation) processes.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The method is versatile as the model fluid can straightforwardly be made to mimic common fluid behaviour like vapour/liquid coexistence, and so fluid systems such as liquid droplets can be simulated.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Also, fluids in complex environments such as porous media can be straightforwardly simulated, whereas with complex boundaries other CFD methods can be hard to work with.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Unlike CFD methods that solve the conservation equations of macroscopic properties (i.e., mass, momentum, and energy) numerically, LBM models the fluid consisting of fictive particles, and such particles perform consecutive propagation and collision processes over a discrete lattice.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Due to its particulate nature and local dynamics, LBM has several advantages over other conventional CFD methods, especially in dealing with complex boundaries, incorporating microscopic interactions, and parallelization of the algorithm.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] A different interpretation of the lattice Boltzmann equation is that of a discrete-velocity Boltzmann equation.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The numerical methods of solution of the system of partial differential equations then give rise to a discrete map, which can be interpreted as the propagation and collision of fictitious particles.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] In an algorithm, there are collision and streaming steps.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] These evolve the density of the fluid $\rho ({\vec {x}},t)$ , for ${\vec {x}}$ the position and t the time.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] As the fluid is on a lattice, the density has a number of components $f_{i},i=0,\ldots ,a$ equal to the number of lattice vectors connected to each lattice point.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] As an example, the lattice vectors for a simple lattice used in simulations in two dimensions is shown here.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] This lattice is usually denoted D2Q9, for two dimensions and nine vectors: four vectors along north, east, south and west, plus four vectors to the corners of a unit square, plus a vector with both components zero.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Then, for example vector ${\vec {e}}_{4}=(0,-1)$ , i.e., it points due south and so has no x component but a y component of $-1$ .
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] So one of the nine components of the total density at the central lattice point, $f_{4}({\vec {x}},t)$ , is that part of the fluid at point ${\vec {x}}$ moving due south, at a speed in lattice units of one.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The model assumes that the fluid locally relaxes to equilibrium over a characteristic timescale $\tau _{f}$ .
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] This timescale determines the kinematic viscosity, the larger it is, the larger is the kinematic viscosity.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] As $f_{i}^{\ast }({\vec {x}},t)$ is, by definition, the fluid density at point ${\vec {x}}$ at time t , that is moving at a velocity of ${\vec {e}}_{i}$ per time step, then at the next time step $t+\delta _{t}$ it will have flowed to point ${\vec {x}}+{\vec {e}}_{i}\delta _{t}$ .
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] As with Navier–Stokes based CFD, LBM methods have been successfully coupled with thermal-specific solutions to enable heat transfer (solids-based conduction, convection and radiation) simulation capability.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] For multiphase/multicomponent models, the interface thickness is usually large and the density ratio across the interface is small when compared with real fluids.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Recently this problem has been resolved by Yuan and Schaefer who improved on models by Shan and Chen, Swift, and He, Chen, and Zhang.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] They were able to reach density ratios of 1000:1 by simply changing the equation of state.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] It has been proposed to apply Galilean Transformation to overcome the limitation of modelling high-speed fluid flows.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] LBM originated from the lattice gas automata (LGA) method, which can be considered as a simplified fictitious molecular dynamics model in which space, time, and particle velocities are all discrete.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] For example, in the 2-dimensional FHP Model each lattice node is connected to its neighbors by 6 lattice velocities on a triangular lattice; there can be either 0 or 1 particles at a lattice node moving with a given lattice velocity.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] After a time interval, each particle will move to the neighboring node in its direction; this process is called the propagation or streaming step.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] When more than one particle arrives at the same node from different directions, they collide and change their velocities according to a set of collision rules.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Streaming steps and collision steps alternate.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Suitable collision rules should conserve the particle number (mass), momentum, and energy before and after the collision.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] LGA suffer from several innate defects for use in hydrodynamic simulations: lack of Galilean invariance for fast flows, statistical noise and poor Reynolds number scaling with lattice size.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] LGA are, however, well suited to simplify and extend the reach of reaction diffusion and molecular dynamics models.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The main motivation for the transition from LGA to LBM was the desire to remove the statistical noise by replacing the Boolean particle number in a lattice direction with its ensemble average, the so-called density distribution function.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Accompanying this replacement, the discrete collision rule is also replaced by a continuous function known as the collision operator.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] In the LBM development, an important simplification is to approximate the collision operator with the Bhatnagar-Gross-Krook (BGK) relaxation term.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] This lattice BGK (LBGK) model makes simulations more efficient and allows flexibility of the transport coefficients.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] On the other hand, it has been shown that the LBM scheme can also be considered as a special discretized form of the continuous Boltzmann equation.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] From Chapman-Enskog theory, one can recover the governing continuity and Navier–Stokes equations from the LBM algorithm.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Lattice Boltzmann models can be operated on a number of different lattices, both cubic and triangular, and with or without rest particles in the discrete distribution function.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] A popular way of classifying the different methods by lattice is the D*n*Q*m* scheme.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Here "D*n*" stands for "*n* dimensions", while "Q*m*" stands for "*m* speeds".
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] For example, D3Q15 is a 3-dimensional lattice Boltzmann model on a cubic grid, with rest particles present.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Each node has a crystal shape and can deliver particles to 15 nodes: each of the 6 neighboring nodes that share a surface, the 8 neighboring nodes sharing a corner, and itself.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Real quantities as space and time need to be converted to lattice units prior to simulation.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Nondimensional quantities, like the Reynolds number, remain the same.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] In most Lattice Boltzmann simulations $\delta _{x}\,\!$ is the basic unit for lattice spacing, so if the domain of length $L\,\!$ has $N\,\!$ lattice units along its entire length, the space unit is simply defined as $\delta _{x}=L/N\,\!$ .
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Speeds in lattice Boltzmann simulations are typically given in terms of the speed of sound.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The discrete time unit can therefore be given as $\delta _{t}={\frac {\delta _{x}}{C_{s}}}\,\!$ , where the denominator $C_{s}$ is the physical speed of sound.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] For small-scale flows (such as those seen in porous media mechanics), operating with the true speed of sound can lead to unacceptably short time steps.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] It is therefore common to raise the lattice Mach number to something much larger than the real Mach number, and compensating for this by raising the viscosity as well in order to preserve the Reynolds number.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Simulating multiphase/multicomponent flows has always been a challenge to conventional CFD because of the moving and deformable interfaces.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] More fundamentally, the interfaces between different phases (liquid and vapor) or components (e.g., oil and water) originate from the specific interactions among fluid molecules.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Therefore, it is difficult to implement such microscopic interactions into the macroscopic Navier–Stokes equation.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] However, in LBM, the particulate kinetics provides a relatively easy and consistent way to incorporate the underlying microscopic interactions by modifying the collision operator.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Several LBM multiphase/multicomponent models have been developed.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Here phase separations are generated automatically from the particle dynamics and no special treatment is needed to manipulate the interfaces as in traditional CFD methods.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Successful applications of multiphase/multicomponent LBM models can be found in various complex fluid systems, including interface instability, bubble/droplet dynamics, wetting on solid surfaces, interfacial slip, and droplet electrohydrodynamic deformations.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] A lattice Boltzmann model for simulation of gas mixture combustion capable of accommodating significant density variations at low-Mach number regime has been recently proposed.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] To this respect, it is worth to notice that, since LBM deals with a larger set of fields (as compared to conventional CFD), the simulation of reactive gas mixtures presents some additional challenges in terms of memory demand as far as large detailed combustion mechanisms are concerned.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Those issues may be addressed, though, by resorting to systematic model reduction techniques.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Currently (2009), a thermal lattice-Boltzmann method (TLBM) falls into one of three categories: the multi-speed approach, the passive scalar approach, and the thermal energy distribution.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Starting with the discrete lattice Boltzmann equation (also referred to as LBGK equation due to the collision operator used).
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] We first do a 2nd-order Taylor series expansion about the left side of the LBE.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] This is chosen over a simpler 1st-order Taylor expansion as the discrete LBE cannot be recovered.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] By substituting the expanded equilibrium and non-equilibrium into the Taylor expansion and separating into different orders of K , the continuum equations are nearly derived.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The equilibrium distribution is only valid for small velocities or small Mach numbers.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] This derivation follows the work of Chen and Doolen.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] F is an external force, $\Omega$ is a collision integral, and ${\vec {e}}$ (also labeled by ${\vec {\xi }}$ in literature) is the microscopic velocity.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The external force F is related to temperature external force G by the relation below.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] A typical test for one's model is the Rayleigh–Bénard convection for G .
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The lattice Boltzmann method discretizes this equation by limiting space to a lattice and the velocity space to a discrete set of microscopic velocities (i. e. ${\vec {e}}_{i}=({\vec {e}}_{ix},{\vec {e}}_{iy})$ ).
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] In the collision operator $f_{i}^{\text{eq}}$ is the discrete, equilibrium particle probability distribution function.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] In D2Q9 and D3Q19, it is shown below for an incompressible flow in continuous and discrete form where *D*, *R*, and *T* are the dimension, universal gas constant, and absolute temperature respectively.
[src:computational-physics/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The partial derivation for the continuous to discrete form is provided through a simple derivation to second order accuracy.
