[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] In physics and astronomy, an ***N*-body simulation** is a simulation of a dynamical system of particles, usually under the influence of physical forces, such as gravity (see *n*-body problem for other applications).
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] *N*-body simulations are widely used tools in astrophysics, from investigating the dynamics of few-body systems like the Earth-Moon-Sun system to understanding the evolution of the large-scale structure of the universe.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] In physical cosmology, *N*-body simulations are used to study processes of non-linear structure formation such as galaxy filaments and galaxy halos from the influence of dark matter.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Direct *N*-body simulations are used to study the dynamical evolution of star clusters.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] The 'particles' treated by the simulation may or may not correspond to physical objects which are particulate in nature.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] For example, an N-body simulation of a star cluster might have a particle per star, so each particle has some physical significance.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] This quantity need not have any physical significance, but must be chosen as a compromise between accuracy and manageable computer requirements.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Dark matter plays an important role in the formation of galaxies.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] In the equation, $\mathbf {v}$ is the velocity, and Φ is the gravitational potential given by Poisson's Equation.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] These two coupled equations are solved in an expanding background Universe, which is governed by the Friedmann equations, after determining the initial conditions of dark matter particles.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] The conventional method employed for initializing positions and velocities of dark matter particles involves moving particles within a uniform Cartesian lattice or a glass-like particle configuration.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] This is done by using a linear theory approximation or a low-order perturbation theory.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] In direct gravitational *N*-body simulations, the equations of motion of a system of *N* particles under the influence of their mutual gravitational forces are integrated numerically without any simplifying approximations.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] These calculations are used in situations where interactions between individual objects, such as stars or planets, are important to the evolution of the system.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] The first purely calculational simulations were then done by Sebastian von Hoerner at the Astronomisches Rechen-Institut in Heidelberg, Germany.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Regularization is a mathematical trick to remove the singularity in the Newtonian law of gravitation for two particles which approach each other arbitrarily close.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Sverre Aarseth's codes are used to study the dynamics of star clusters, planetary systems and galactic nuclei.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Many simulations are large enough that the effects of general relativity in establishing a Friedmann-Lemaitre-Robertson-Walker cosmology are significant.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] This is incorporated in the simulation as an evolving measure of distance (or scale factor) in a comoving coordinate system, which causes the particles to slow in comoving coordinates (as well as due to the redshifting of their physical energy).
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] However, the contributions of general relativity and the finite speed of gravity can otherwise be ignored, as typical dynamical timescales are long compared to the light crossing time for the simulation, and the space-time curvature induced by the particles and the particle velocities are small.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] The boundary conditions of these cosmological simulations are usually periodic (or toroidal), so that one edge of the simulation volume matches up with the opposite edge.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Numerical integration is usually performed over small timesteps using a method such as leapfrog integration.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] However all numerical integration leads to errors.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Smaller steps give lower errors but run more slowly.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Leapfrog integration is roughly 2nd order on the timestep, other integrators such as Runge–Kutta methods can have 4th order accuracy or much higher.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] One of the simplest refinements is that each particle carries with it its own timestep variable, so that particles with widely different dynamical times don't all have to be evolved forward at the rate of that with the shortest time.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] There are two basic approximation schemes to decrease the computational time for such simulations.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] These can reduce the computational complexity to O(N log N) or better, at the loss of accuracy.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] This can dramatically reduce the number of particle pair interactions that must be computed.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] To prevent the simulation from becoming swamped by computing particle-particle interactions, the cells must be refined to smaller cells in denser parts of the simulation which contain many particles per cell.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] For simulations where particles are not evenly distributed, the well-separated pair decomposition methods of Callahan and Kosaraju yield optimal O(*n* log *n*) time per iteration with fixed dimension.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Another possibility is the particle mesh method in which space is discretised on a mesh and, for the purposes of computing the gravitational potential, particles are assumed to be divided between the surrounding 2x2 vertices of the mesh.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] where *G* is Newton's constant and $\rho$ is the density (number of particles at the mesh points).
