[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Since this method is limited by the mesh size, in practice a smaller mesh or some other technique (such as combining with a tree or simple particle-particle algorithm) is used to compute the small-scale forces.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Sometimes an adaptive mesh is used, in which the mesh cells are much smaller in the denser regions of the simulation.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Several different gravitational perturbation algorithms are used to get fairly accurate estimates of the path of objects in the Solar System.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] People often decide to put a satellite in a frozen orbit.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] The path of a satellite closely orbiting the Earth can be accurately modeled starting from the 2-body elliptical orbit around the center of the Earth, and adding small corrections due to the oblateness of the Earth, gravitational attraction of the Sun and Moon, atmospheric drag, etc.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] It is possible to find a frozen orbit without calculating the actual path of the satellite.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] The path of a small planet, comet, or long-range spacecraft can often be accurately modeled starting from the 2-body elliptical orbit around the Sun, and adding small corrections from the gravitational attraction of the larger planets in their known orbits.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Some characteristics of the long-term paths of a system of particles can be calculated directly.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] The actual path of any particular particle does not need to be calculated as an intermediate step.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Such characteristics include Lyapunov stability, Lyapunov time, various measurements from ergodic theory, etc.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Although there are millions or billions of particles in typical simulations, they typically correspond to a real particle with a very large mass, typically 109 solar masses.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] This can introduce problems with short-range interactions between the particles such as the formation of two-particle binary systems.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] As the particles are meant to represent large numbers of dark matter particles or groups of stars, these binaries are unphysical.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] To prevent this, a softened Newtonian force law is used, which does not diverge as the inverse-square radius at short distances.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Most simulations implement this quite naturally by running the simulations on cells of finite size.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] It is important to implement the discretization procedure in such a way that particles always exert a vanishing force on themselves.
