[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Many simulations simulate only cold dark matter, and thus include only the gravitational force.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Incorporating baryons, leptons and photons into the simulations dramatically increases their complexity and often radical simplifications of the underlying physics must be made.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] However, this is an extremely important area and many modern simulations are now trying to understand processes that occur during galaxy formation which could account for galaxy bias.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] On the other hand, if the question is whether the body *eventually* reaches the destination ball, the problem is PSPACE-hard.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] These bounds are based on similar complexity bounds obtained for ray tracing.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] The simplest implementation of N-body simulations where ${\textstyle n\geq 3}$ is a naive propagation of orbiting bodies; naive implying that the only forces acting on the orbiting bodies is the gravitational force which they exert on each other.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] This method is applicable to other types of N-body simulations as well; a simulation of point masses with charges would use a similar method, however the force would be due to attraction or repulsion by interaction of electric fields.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Additionally, `OrbitalEntity` contains enough room for a mass value.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Commonly, N-body simulations will be systems based on some type of equations of motion; of these, most will be dependent on some initial configuration to "seed" the simulation.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] In systems such as those dependent on some gravitational or electric potential, the force on a simulation entity is independent on its velocity.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Hence, to seed the *forces* of the simulation, merely initial positions are needed, but this will not allow propagation- initial velocities are required.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Consider a planet orbiting a star- it has no motion, but is subject to gravitational attraction to its host star.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] As a time progresses, and time *steps* are added, it will gather velocity according to its acceleration.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] For a given instant in time, $t_{n}$ , the resultant acceleration of a body due to its neighbouring masses is independent of its velocity, however, for the time step $t_{n+1}$ , the resulting change in position is significantly different due the propagation's inherent dependency on velocity.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] Without acceleration, ${\textstyle {\vec {v}}_{t_{n}}}$ is static, however, from the perspective of an observer seeing only position, it will take two time steps to see a change in velocity.
[src:computational-physics/n-body-simulation] A solar-system-like simulation can be accomplished by taking average distances of planet equivalent point masses from a central star.
