[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] In analysis, **numerical integration** comprises a broad family of algorithms for calculating the numerical value of a definite integral.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The term **numerical quadrature** (often abbreviated to **quadrature**) is more or less a synonym for "numerical integration", especially as applied to one-dimensional integrals.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Some authors refer to numerical integration over more than one dimension as **cubature**; others take "quadrature" to include higher-dimensional integration.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] If *f*(*x*) is a smooth function integrated over a small number of dimensions, and the domain of integration is bounded, there are many methods for approximating the integral to the desired precision.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Numerical integration has roots in the geometrical problem of finding a square with the same area as a given plane figure (*quadrature* or *squaring*), as in the quadrature of the circle.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The term is also sometimes used to describe the numerical solution of differential equations.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] A formula for the integrand may be known, but it may be difficult or impossible to find an antiderivative that is an elementary function.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] An example of such an integrand is *f* (*x*) = exp(−*x*2), the antiderivative of which (the error function, times a constant) cannot be written in elementary form .
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] It may be possible to find an antiderivative symbolically, but it may be easier to compute a numerical approximation than to compute the antiderivative.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] That may be the case if the antiderivative is given as an infinite series or product, or if its evaluation requires a special function that is not available.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The term "numerical integration" first appears in 1915 in the publication *A Course in Interpolation and Numeric Integration for the Mathematical Laboratory* by David Gibb.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] "Quadrature" is a historical mathematical term that means calculating area.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Quadrature problems have served as one of the main sources of mathematical analysis.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Mathematicians of Ancient Greece, according to the Pythagorean doctrine, understood calculation of area as the process of constructing geometrically a square having the same area (*squaring*) — that is why the process was named "quadrature".
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Examples include quadrature of the circle, Lune of Hippocrates, and the treatise *Quadrature of the Parabola*.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] This construction must be performed only by means of compass and straightedge.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The ancient Babylonians used the trapezoidal rule to integrate the motion of Jupiter along the ecliptic.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] For a quadrature of a rectangle with the sides *a* and *b* it is necessary to construct a square with the side $x={\sqrt {ab}}$ (the geometric mean of *a* and *b*).
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] For this purpose it is possible to use the following fact: if we draw the circle with the sum of *a* and *b* as the diameter, then the height BH (from a point of their connection to crossing with a circle) equals their geometric mean.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The similar geometrical construction solves a problem of a quadrature for a parallelogram and a triangle.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Problems of quadrature for curvilinear figures are much more difficult.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the circle with compass and straightedge had been proved in the 19th century to be impossible.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Nevertheless, for some figures (for example the lune of Hippocrates) a quadrature can be performed.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The quadratures of a sphere surface and a parabola segment done by Archimedes became the highest achievement of the antique analysis.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] To prove the results, Archimedes used the method of exhaustion of Eudoxus.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] In medieval Europe the quadrature meant calculation of area by any method.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] More often the method of indivisibles was used; it was less rigorous, but more simple and powerful.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] John Wallis algebrised this method: he wrote in his *Arithmetica Infinitorum* (1656) series that we now call the definite integral, and he calculated their values.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Isaac Barrow and James Gregory made further progress: quadratures for some algebraic curves and spirals.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Christiaan Huygens successfully performed a quadrature of some solids of revolution.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the hyperbola by Saint-Vincent and de Sarasa provided a new function, the natural logarithm, of critical importance.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] With the invention of integral calculus came a universal method for area calculation.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] In response, the term "quadrature" has become traditional, and instead the modern phrase "*computation of a univariate definite integral*" is more common.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] A **quadrature rule** is an approximation of the definite integral of a function, usually stated as a weighted sum of function values at specified points within the domain of integration.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Numerical integration methods can generally be described as combining evaluations of the integrand to get an approximation to the integral.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The integrand is evaluated at a finite set of points called ***integration points*** and a weighted sum of these values is used to approximate the integral.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The integration points and weights depend on the specific method used and the accuracy required from the approximation.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] An important part of the analysis of any numerical integration method is to study the behavior of the approximation error as a function of the number of integrand evaluations.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] A method that yields a small error for a small number of evaluations is usually considered superior.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Reducing the number of evaluations of the integrand reduces the number of arithmetic operations involved, and therefore reduces the total error.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Also, each evaluation takes time, and the integrand may be arbitrarily complicated.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] A "brute force" kind of numerical integration can be done, if the integrand is reasonably well-behaved (i.e. piecewise continuous and of bounded variation), by evaluating the integrand with very small increments.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] This simplest method approximates the function by a step function (a piecewise constant function, or a segmented polynomial of degree zero) that passes through the point ${\textstyle \left({\frac {a+b}{2}},f\left({\frac {a+b}{2}}\right)\right)}$ .
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] A large class of quadrature rules can be derived by constructing interpolating functions that are easy to integrate.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Typically these interpolating functions are polynomials.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] In practice, since polynomials of very high degree tend to oscillate wildly, only polynomials of low degree are used, typically linear and quadratic.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The interpolating function may be a straight line (an affine function, i.e. a polynomial of degree 1) passing through the points $\left(a,f(a)\right)$ and $\left(b,f(b)\right)$ .
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] For either one of these rules, we can make a more accurate approximation by breaking up the interval $[a,b]$ into some number n of subintervals, computing an approximation for each subinterval, then adding up all the results.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] This is called a *composite rule*, *extended rule*, or *iterated rule*.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] where the subintervals have the form $[a+kh,a+(k+1)h]\subset [a,b],$ with ${\textstyle h={\frac {b-a}{n}}}$ and $k=0,\ldots ,n-1.$ Here we used subintervals of the same length h but one could also use intervals of varying length $\left(h_{k}\right)_{k}$ .
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Interpolation with polynomials evaluated at equally spaced points in $[a,b]$ yields the Newton–Cotes formulas, of which the rectangle rule and the trapezoidal rule are examples.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Simpson's rule, which is based on a polynomial of order 2, is also a Newton–Cotes formula.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Quadrature rules with equally spaced points have the very convenient property of *nesting*.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The corresponding rule with each interval subdivided includes all the current points, so those integrand values can be re-used.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] If we allow the intervals between interpolation points to vary, we find another group of quadrature formulas, such as the Gaussian quadrature formulas.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] A Gaussian quadrature rule is typically more accurate than a Newton–Cotes rule that uses the same number of function evaluations, if the integrand is smooth (i.e., if it is sufficiently differentiable).
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Other quadrature methods with varying intervals include Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature (also called Fejér quadrature) methods, which do nest.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Gaussian quadrature rules do not nest, but the related Gauss–Kronrod quadrature formulas do.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Adaptive quadrature is a numerical integration method in which the integral of a function $f(x)$ is approximated using static quadrature rules on adaptively refined subintervals of the region of integration.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Generally, adaptive algorithms are just as efficient and effective as traditional algorithms for "well behaved" integrands, but are also effective for "badly behaved" integrands for which traditional algorithms may fail.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The accuracy of a quadrature rule of the Newton–Cotes type is generally a function of the number of evaluation points.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The result is usually more accurate as the number of evaluation points increases, or, equivalently, as the width of the step size between the points decreases.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] It is natural to ask what the result would be if the step size were allowed to approach zero.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] This can be answered by extrapolating the result from two or more nonzero step sizes, using series acceleration methods such as Richardson extrapolation.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The extrapolation function may be a polynomial or rational function.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Extrapolation methods are described in more detail by Stoer and Bulirsch (Section 3.4) and are implemented in many of the routines in the QUADPACK library.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] where the supremum was used to approximate.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Hence, if we approximate the integral ${\textstyle \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx}$ by the quadrature rule $(b-a)f(a)$ our error is no greater than the right hand side of **1**.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] We can convert this into an error analysis for the Riemann sum, giving an upper bound of ${\frac {n^{-1}}{2}}\sup _{0\leq x\leq 1}\left|f'(x)\right|$ for the error term of that particular approximation.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] (Note that this is precisely the error we calculated for the example $f(x)=x$ .) Using more derivatives, and by tweaking the quadrature, we can do a similar error analysis using a Taylor series (using a partial sum with remainder term) for *f*.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] This error analysis gives a strict upper bound on the error, if the derivatives of *f* are available.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] This integration method can be combined with interval arithmetic to produce computer proofs and *verified* calculations.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Several methods exist for approximate integration over unbounded intervals.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The standard technique involves specially derived quadrature rules, such as Gauss-Hermite quadrature for integrals on the whole real line and Gauss-Laguerre quadrature for integrals on the positive reals.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The quadrature rules discussed so far are all designed to compute one-dimensional integrals.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] To compute integrals in multiple dimensions, one approach is to phrase the multiple integral as repeated one-dimensional integrals by applying Fubini's theorem (the tensor product rule).
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] This approach requires the function evaluations to grow exponentially as the number of dimensions increases.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Three methods are known to overcome this so-called *curse of dimensionality*.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] A great many additional techniques for forming multidimensional cubature integration rules for a variety of weighting functions are given in the monograph by Stroud.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Integration on the sphere has been reviewed by Hesse et al.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Monte Carlo methods and quasi-Monte Carlo methods are easy to apply to multi-dimensional integrals.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] They may yield greater accuracy for the same number of function evaluations than repeated integrations using one-dimensional methods.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] A large class of useful Monte Carlo methods are the so-called Markov chain Monte Carlo algorithms, which include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm and Gibbs sampling.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Sparse grids were originally developed by Smolyak for the quadrature of high-dimensional functions.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The method is always based on a one-dimensional quadrature rule, but performs a more sophisticated combination of univariate results.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] However, whereas the tensor product rule guarantees that the weights of all of the cubature points will be positive if the weights of the quadrature points were positive, Smolyak's rule does not guarantee that the weights will all be positive.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Bayesian quadrature is a statistical approach to the numerical problem of computing integrals and falls under the field of probabilistic numerics.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] It can provide a full handling of the uncertainty over the solution of the integral expressed as a Gaussian process posterior variance.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] can be reduced to an initial value problem for an ordinary differential equation by applying the first part of the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Numerical methods for ordinary differential equations, such as Runge–Kutta methods, can be applied to the restated problem and thus be used to evaluate the integral.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] For instance, the standard fourth-order Runge–Kutta method applied to the differential equation yields Simpson's rule from above.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The differential equation $F'(x)=f(x)$ has a special form: the right-hand side contains only the independent variable (here x ) and not the dependent variable (here F ).
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] This simplifies the theory and algorithms considerably.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] The problem of evaluating integrals is thus best studied in its own right.
[src:computational-physics/numerical-integration] Conversely, the term "quadrature" may also be used for the solution of differential equations: "solving by quadrature" or "reduction to quadrature" means expressing its solution in terms of integrals.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] This equation, for various choices of the potential function V , can be used to describe the evolution of diverse physical systems, from the motion of interacting molecules to the orbit of the planets.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Typically, an initial position $\mathbf {x} (0)=\mathbf {x} _{0}$ and an initial velocity $\mathbf {v} (0)={\dot {\mathbf {x} }}(0)=\mathbf {v} _{0}$ are also given.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] To discretize and numerically solve this initial value problem, a time step $\Delta t>0$ is chosen, and the sampling-point sequence $t_{n}=n\,\Delta t$ considered.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The task is to construct a sequence of points $\mathbf {x} _{n}$ that closely follow the points $\mathbf {x} (t_{n})$ on the trajectory of the exact solution.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The time symmetry inherent in the method reduces the level of local errors introduced into the integration by the discretization by removing all odd-degree terms, here the terms in $\Delta t$ of degree three.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Caution should be applied to the fact that the acceleration here is computed from the exact solution, $\mathbf {a} (t)=\mathbf {A} {\bigl (}\mathbf {x} (t){\bigr )}$ , whereas in the iteration it is computed at the central iteration point, $\mathbf {a} _{n}=\mathbf {A} (\mathbf {x} _{n})$ .
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] In computing the global error, that is the distance between exact solution and approximation sequence, those two terms do not cancel exactly, influencing the order of the global error.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] To gain insight into the relation of local and global errors, it is helpful to examine simple examples where the exact solution, as well as the approximate solution, can be expressed in explicit formulas.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The standard example for this task is the exponential function.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Consider the linear differential equation ${\ddot {x}}(t)=w^{2}x(t)$ with a constant w .
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Its exact basis solutions are $e^{wt}$ and $e^{-wt}$ .
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Note that at the start of the Verlet iteration at step $n=1$ , time $t=t_{1}=\Delta t$ , computing $\mathbf {x} _{2}$ , one already needs the position vector $\mathbf {x} _{1}$ at time $t=t_{1}$ .
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] At first sight, this could give problems, because the initial conditions are known only at the initial time $t_{0}=0$ .
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The error on the first time step then is of order ${\mathcal {O}}{\left(\Delta t^{3}\right)}$ .
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Moreover, to obtain this second-order global error, the initial error needs to be of at least third order.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] A disadvantage of the Størmer–Verlet method is that if the time step ( $\Delta t$ ) changes, the method does not approximate the solution to the differential equation.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The velocities are not explicitly given in the basic Størmer equation, but often they are necessary for the calculation of certain physical quantities like the kinetic energy.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] This can create technical challenges in molecular dynamics simulations, because kinetic energy and instantaneous temperatures at time t cannot be calculated for a system until the positions are known at time $t+\Delta t$ .
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Note that this velocity term is a step behind the position term, since this is for the velocity at time t , not $t+\Delta t$ , meaning that $\mathbf {v} _{n}={\tfrac {\mathbf {x} _{n+1}-\mathbf {x} _{n-1}}{2\Delta t}}$ is a second-order approximation to $\mathbf {v} (t_{n})$ .
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] A related, and more commonly used algorithm is the velocity Verlet algorithm, similar to the leapfrog method, except that the velocity and position are calculated at the same value of the time variable (leapfrog does not, as the name suggests).
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] It can be shown that the error in the velocity Verlet is of the same order as in the basic Verlet.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Note that the velocity algorithm is not necessarily more memory-consuming, because, in basic Verlet, we keep track of two vectors of position, while in velocity Verlet, we keep track of one vector of position and one vector of velocity.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Derive $\mathbf {a} (t+\Delta t)$ from the interaction potential using $\mathbf {x} (t+\Delta t)$ .
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] This algorithm also works with variable time steps, and is identical to the 'kick-drift-kick' form of leapfrog method integration.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Note, however, that this algorithm assumes that acceleration $\mathbf {a} (t+\Delta t)$ only depends on position $\mathbf {x} (t+\Delta t)$ and does not depend on velocity $\mathbf {v} (t+\Delta t)$ .
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] One might note that the long-term results of velocity Verlet, and similarly of leapfrog are one order better than the semi-implicit Euler method.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The algorithms are almost identical up to a shift by half a time step in the velocity.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] This can be proven by rotating the above loop to start at step 3 and then noticing that the acceleration term in step 1 could be eliminated by combining steps 2 and 4.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The only difference is that the midpoint velocity in velocity Verlet is considered the final velocity in semi-implicit Euler method.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The global error of all Euler methods is of order one, whereas the global error of this method is, similar to the midpoint method, of order two.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The same goes for all other conserved quantities of the system like linear or angular momentum, that are always preserved or nearly preserved in a symplectic integrator.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The velocity Verlet method is a special case of the Newmark-beta method with $\beta =0$ and ${\textstyle \gamma ={\tfrac {1}{2}}}$ .
