[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] This type of position integration will significantly increase accuracy in 3D simulations and games when compared with the regular Euler method.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The global truncation error of the Verlet method is ${\mathcal {O}}{\left(\Delta t^{2}\right)}$ , both for position and velocity.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] This is in contrast with the fact that the local error in position is only ${\mathcal {O}}{\left(\Delta t^{4}\right)}$ as described above.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The difference is due to the accumulation of the local truncation error over all of the iterations.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Because the velocity is determined in a non-cumulative way from the positions in the Verlet integrator, the global error in velocity is also ${\mathcal {O}}{\left(\Delta t^{2}\right)}$ .
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] In molecular dynamics simulations, the global error is typically far more important than the local error, and the Verlet integrator is therefore known as a second-order integrator.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Systems of multiple particles with constraints are simpler to solve with Verlet integration than with Euler methods.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Constraints between points may be, for example, potentials constraining them to a specific distance or attractive forces.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] They may be modeled as springs connecting the particles.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Using springs of infinite stiffness, the model may then be solved with a Verlet algorithm.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Verlet integration is useful because it directly relates the force to the position, rather than solving the problem using velocities.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Problems, however, arise when multiple constraining forces act on each particle.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] One way to solve this is to loop through every point in a simulation, so that at every point the constraint relaxation of the last is already used to speed up the spread of the information.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] In a simulation this may be implemented by using small time steps for the simulation, using a fixed number of constraint-solving steps per time step, or solving constraints until they are met by a specific deviation.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] When approximating the constraints locally to first order, this is the same as the Gauss–Seidel method.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] For small matrices it is known that LU decomposition is faster.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Large systems can be divided into clusters (for example, each ragdoll = cluster).
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Inside clusters the LU method is used, between clusters the Gauss–Seidel method is used.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The matrix code can be reused: The dependency of the forces on the positions can be approximated locally to first order, and the Verlet integration can be made more implicit.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Sophisticated software, such as SuperLU exists to solve complex problems using sparse matrices.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Specific techniques, such as using (clusters of) matrices, may be used to address the specific problem, such as that of force propagating through a sheet of cloth without forming a sound wave.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Another way to solve holonomic constraints is to use constraint algorithms.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] One way of reacting to collisions is to use a penalty-based system, which basically applies a set force to a point upon contact.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The problem with this is that it is very difficult to choose the force imparted.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Use too strong a force, and objects will become unstable, too weak, and the objects will penetrate each other.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Another way is to use projection collision reactions, which takes the offending point and attempts to move it the shortest distance possible to move it out of the other object.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The Verlet integration would automatically handle the velocity imparted by the collision in the latter case; however, note that this is not guaranteed to do so in a way that is consistent with collision physics (that is, changes in momentum are not guaranteed to be realistic).
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] Instead of implicitly changing the velocity term, one would need to explicitly control the final velocities of the objects colliding (by changing the recorded position from the previous time step).
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] The two simplest methods for deciding on a new velocity are perfectly elastic and inelastic collisions.
[src:computational-physics/verlet-integration] A slightly more complicated strategy that offers more control would involve using the coefficient of restitution.
